						<p class="mt-4 text-[1.2rem] sm:ml-8">
							Mission-oriented organizations rely on social incentives in the absence of
							high-powered pecuniary incentives. We identify a novel social incentive with
							significant impact on motivation. We present evidence on how agents' motivation is
							affected when they share personal traits - in our setting localized regional identity
							- with a principal. Using individual‚Äêlevel data on all French WWI fatalities, we
							estimate the effect of losing such connection. In a design-based
							difference-in-difference setup we exploit within-regiment variation across regional
							groups. We find that soldiers (agents) are more motivated when a principal (officer)
							with a shared identity is present. Placebo treatments - a random draw of non-connected
							officers dying - support a causal interpretation of our results. Heterogeneity
							analysis reveals that regional network effects matter most for minority groups in
							non-diverse regiments. By exploring how our effect varies across regions we can also
							speak to the determinants of regional cultural identity in France in the early 19th
							century.
						</p>
