						<p class="mt-4 text-[1.2rem] sm:ml-8">
							Reproductive inequality - the fertility differential between poor and rich couples -
							together with intergenerational mobility shapes class structure. Still, few studies
							evaluate these dynamics in a joint framework. Evolutionary growth theories such as
							Galor & Moav (2002) or Clark (2007) argue that fertility differentials contributed to
							the spread of certain growth-enhancing traits, eventually resulting in modern economic
							growth. However, they do not explicitly account for regression to the mean in economic
							status. By leveraging the demographic records of 150,000 individuals from
							pre-industrial Germany, I estimate reproductive inequality and social mobility. High
							status couples had more surviving children, with their status closely related to their
							parents' position in the socio-economic distribution. By combining my estimates of
							reproductive inequality and social mobility I simulate an overlapping generation model
							to explore the parameter space that enables the demographic mechanisms that underpin
							evolutionary growth theories.
						</p>
